<DOC><DOCNO> AP890909-0113 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-89 1708EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-09 0500</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0514</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Thunderstorms Across Southern Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy rain fell Saturday across the southern Plains as showersand thunderstorms developed ahead of a cold front that stretchedfrom the southern Plains to the upper Great Lakes.   Late Friday, severe thunderstorms hit parts of Missouri, Kansasand Nebraska, and the heavy rain continued Saturday from southernTexas across Arkansas and Kansas into southern Missouri.   Eureka, Ark., got nearly 3 inches of rain in 6 hours during themorning.   The Kansas City, Mo., area got 4.5 inches of rain in the stormsfrom Friday into Saturday.   Rivers and streams rose across northeastern Kansas, southeasternNebraska and northwestern Missouri.   Minor flooding occurred along the Republican River near ClayCenter, Kan., and several rural roads in the area were closed bywater, the National Weather Service said.   The Platte River at Platte City, Mo., is expected to rise to 10feet above flood stage by Monday morning and the Missouri River atSt. Joseph, Mo., already 2 feet above flood stage, was expected toclimb 7 feet above flood stage, the weather service said.   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the TennesseeValley and along the Gulf Coast, and showers extended from Iowa intothe upper Great Lakes.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included1.06 inches at Milwaukee and 1.02 inches at Springfield, Mo.   Cool, moist air pushing into the northern and central Rockiesproduced showers, with snow at higher elevations. In Wyoming, up to5 inches of snow fell across the Wind River range and the LaramieRange received a half-inch of snow.   Afternoon temperatures were only in the 40s and 50s from thenorthern and central Rockies across much of North Dakota intonorthern Minnesota.   Great Falls, Mont., tied its record low for the date of 31degrees.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 39degrees at Riverton, Wyo., to 98 at Harlingen, Waco and Austin,Texas, and Palm Springs, Calif. Saturday morning's low in the Lower48 states was 26 at Gunnison, Colo.   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from theeastern half of the southern Plains and the lower Mississippi Valleyacross the Ohio Valley and the eastern half of the Great Lakesregion to northern New England. Scattered showers were forecast fromthe northern Plains and Nebraska into the northern and centralRockies. Snow was forecast at higher elevations of the northernRockies.   Highs in the 40s were predicted over northwestern and centralMontana; in the 50s and 60s from Idaho across Wyoming, the northernPlains and the upper Mississippi Valley to the western half of theupper Great Lakes region; in the 90s from the southern AtlanticCoast and Florida across the Tennessee Valley and the Gulf Coast tosouthern and eastern Texas; between 90 and 105 across the desertSouthwest into interior valleys of California; and in the 70s and80s across much of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>